        "name": "Test samples acceptance criteria — production representativeness",
        "description": "Test specimens must be production-representative parts from the same manufacturing lot, with CMM verification that key dimensions (screw OD, thread pitch, rod diameter) are within production drawing tolerances. N≥8 per laboratory. Achieved: N=11 specimens across two labs, all from production lot, CMM-verified within tolerance."
      },
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories. All specimens are production-representative parts from the same manufacturing lot, CMM-verified. Inter-laboratory variability characterized and within acceptable bounds (CV <4% for stiffness)."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-cou1-tc",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The ASTM F1717 standard specifies a single, fully prescribed test configuration for static compression-bending: load application axis, UHMWPE block geometry, grip separation (100 mm), and displacement rate (5 mm/min) are all normatively fixed. There is no provision within the standard for varying test conditions, and the regulatory submission context requires strict adherence to the standardized protocol. Consequently, the concept of assessing 'range of test conditions' as contemplated by the ASME V&V 40 Test Conditions factor — which envisions varying environmental parameters, loading rates, or boundary condition configurations to characterize model robustness — is inapplicable here: only one test condition exists by design. Applying a multi-condition assessment framework to a single-condition standardized test would produce a vacuous result and does not add credibility evidence. This determination was reviewed by the credibility assessment team and concurred with by the regulatory affairs representative. The single-condition limitation is instead documented as a scope boundary in the decision record, and the overall credibility argument relies on the high fidelity of the single-condition comparison (E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs) rather than multi-condition coverage."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-cou1-eip",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-cou1-eip-ac",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Equivalency of input parameters acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Model boundary conditions, load magnitudes, and geometric inputs must be demonstrably equivalent to the physical test setup, with all discrepancies documented and their effect on QoIs bounded. Achieved: CMM-verified geometry used directly in FEA; load application point and grip separation replicated exactly; discrepancy analysis shows <0.5% QoI effect from remaining geometric idealizations."
      },
      "rationale": "FEA boundary conditions replicate the ASTM F1717 test configuration: UHMWPE block geometry from CMM, grip separation 100 mm, displacement-controlled loading at 5 mm/min equivalent quasi-static rate. All geometric idealizations (fillet radii, thread root simplification) assessed via sensitivity runs and shown to contribute <0.5% to QoI predictions."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-cou1-oc",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-cou1-oc-ac",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criteria — E/uval metric",
        "description": "Validation metric E/uval must be <1.96 for all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) across both laboratories. Point estimates must differ by <10%. Achieved: E/uval = 0.83 (stiffness), 1.12 (yield force), 0.97 (force at 40 mm); all point differences <6%."
      },
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison using the ASME V&V 40 validation metric E/uval, incorporating both simulation and experimental uncertainty. All three QoIs pass the acceptance criterion across both laboratories. Gradation 4 reflects use of a rigorous uncertainty-normalized metric with full uncertainty propagation on both sides of the comparison."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-cou1-rqoi",
